subject: Re: [opensuse] Update runs in loop...Amarak/Fix to improve stability and...
body: On Sunday 10 February 2008 11:52:28 pm Verner KjÃ¦rsgaard wrote: > Hi list. > > - brand new OpenSuSE10.3, plain vanilla. > > - my orange "updates are ready for you" icon in my KDE taskbar  encourages > me to update the mentioned Amarok/Fix to.. > > - it keeps doing so, it never seems to realize that I've done that and done > that and done that and...you get the picture. It never goes green. > > - how do I tell the blasted thing to put a sock in it ? Mine did that for awhile. Some Amarok update that wouldn't get installed. I eventually opened YaST software (also just Install Software and chose  Package > All Packages > Update if newer version available. My updater is now green. --  >From twaoslx@goodship.net  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message: 3 Date: Wed, 06 Feb 2008 15:42:59 -0500 From: Armando Di Cianno  Subject: Re: [TuxOnIce-users] [TuxOnIce-devel] 3.0-rc5 released. To: TuxOnIce users' list  Message-ID: <1202330579.9823.47.camel@localhost.localdomain> Content-Type: text/plain On Wed, 2008-02-06 at 15:31 -0500, Mark Beierl wrote: > I'm getting the hang during writing caches quite consistently.  Kernel > 2.6.24, 3.0-rc5. >  > I have upgraded to nvidia 169.09, but it still hangs anywhere from 1/3 > to 2/3 of the way through writing caches.  I've got 3gb of memory > installed, so that would be anywhere between 1 and 2 gb written:) >  > I have not tried explicitly running glxgears prior to hibernation.  Does > that actually make a difference? nvidia drivers ~ 100.14 or so, I had to run glxgears fairly consistently, to get hibernation to work reliably. However, I'm seeing intermittent hangs with 169.09, still, also at writing caches.  I have 4GB of RAM, on a 32-bit system with highmem. I'm not sure where we can go from here -- bug reports to nvidia, maybe? --  __armando http://dicianno.org/blog twaoslx@goodship.net twaoslx@dicianno.org ------------------------------ >From azaklwk.hbyumeak@habmalnefrage.de  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message: 4 Date: Thu, 07 Feb 2008 09:19:57 +0100 From: Michael Schmarck  Subject: Re: [TuxOnIce-users] Count to 100 To: enpsfhxz-stvnz@lists.tuxonice.net Message-ID: <2008774.VKB331A1HL@michael-schmarck.my-fqdn.de> Content-Type: text/plain; charset Nigel Cunningham  wrote: > It sounds like you enabled the TuxOnIce pageflags debugging module, and > compiled it in to your kernel. I would deselect it completely. After disabling that option, I now longer have that count. Thanks a lot! Michael ------------------------------ >From azaklwk.hbyumeak@habmalnefrage.de  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message: 5 Date: Thu, 07 Feb 2008 10:38:36 +0100 From: Michael Schmarck  Subject: Re: [TuxOnIce-users] [TuxOnIce-devel] 3.0-rc5 released. To: enpsfhxz-stvnz@lists.tuxonice.net Message-ID: <2202273.AUoP8XnSf2@michael-schmarck.my-fqdn.de> Content-Type: text/plain; charset Armando Di Cianno  wrote: > nvidia drivers ~ 100.14 or so, I had to run glxgears fairly > consistently, to get hibernation to work reliably. I'm not saying that I have much experience, but in the last few days, I forgot (without intent) to run glxgears prior to doing the hibernation, and I had good success! No hang anymore (despite my post from last Friday). I'm also using 169.09. Michael ------------------------------ _______________________________________________ TuxOnIce-users mailing list enpsfhxz-stvnz@lists.tuxonice.net http://lists.tuxonice.net/mailman/listinfo/tuxonice-users

subject: Re: [opensuse] openSUSE 11.0 and the Non-ready KDE4
body: On Monday 11 February 2008 03:10:26 am Alexey Eremenko wrote: > Hi all ! > > Just installed openSUSE 11.0, with a KDE 4 desktop, and I can say that > it is not ready. > > Not only it is full of bugs and crashes, but it is also lacks > features.  Meh - how many crashes did it have for you?  It looks pretty, but not very  usable.  :P > Very likely, that KDE 4 will not be ready for openSUSE 11.0  > final. I dunno - Jolt Cola can do wonders to an Operating System... > It is highly unlikely that even KDE 4.1 will be stable-enough and > feature complete for day-to-day usage. No - we're gonna have to wait for KDE 5.0, as it will be an odd-numbered  version. > > Please provide an option to choose KDE3 desktop during setup. > Otherwise all KDE users will be in big trouble with openSUSE 11. I doubt they'd release a buggy 4.0 on a major distribution point version such  as 11.0. --  >From nhjqtw.satghl@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org From: jeevs  Subject: Re: Email from windows Date: Wed, 6 Feb 2008 21:56:12 -0800 (PST) Message-ID: <7d7c1b21-8f3a-465b-b1f7-f421a0bc2ec1@m62g2000hsb.googlegroups.com> Mime-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Thanks everyone.. I figured the smtp server for my domain which I was using incorrectly.. Thanks for it --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98646.ezm" >From keanxldzleux@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org From: keanxldzleux@gmail.com Subject: Calling Tomahawk tool in perl script Date: Wed, 6 Feb 2008 05:38:10 -0800 (PST) Message-ID: <272607e8-29da-47bf-bbb2-ad3262093ab7@u10g2000prn.googlegroups.com> Mime-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Hi, I have a query of how to call Tomahawk in perl. Tomahawk is a tool used in Linux for verifying NIPS. I need to get the Tomahawks attribute from the user and pass it to tomahawk tool. If anyone has any idea about how to call the Tomahawk tool within perl script..kindly reply. Thanks in advance -Sandy --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98647.ezm" >From abk@stonehenge.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <31086b240802061145l814cdadp82c62f182b325c01@mail.gmail.com> Date: Wed, 6 Feb 2008 11:45:46 -0800 From: "Tom Phoenix"  To: keanxldzleux@gmail.com Subject: Re: Calling Tomahawk tool in perl script Cc: soiofdvxg@perl.org MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit On Feb 6, 2008 5:38 AM,   wrote: > I have a query of how to call Tomahawk in perl. Tomahawk is a tool > used in > Linux for verifying NIPS. I need to get the Tomahawks attribute from > the user and pass it to tomahawk tool. If anyone has any idea about > how to call the Tomahawk tool within perl script..kindly reply. You can run another program in many ways from Perl. You might want system().     my $result = system 'tomahawk',         '-f', $packet_trace_file_name;  # or whatever Did I guess correctly that you want to run another program from Perl? If not, perhaps you should explain in more detail what you want to do. Hope this helps! --Tom Phoenix Stonehenge Perl Training --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98648.ezm" >From ahlg.rwhsv@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <58ce48dc0802061148va5e4e21la1f736ff18a8375a@mail.gmail.com> Date: Wed, 6 Feb 2008 14:48:06 -0500 From: "Chas. Owens"  To: keanxldzleux@gmail.com Subject: Re: Calling Tomahawk tool in perl script Cc: soiofdvxg@perl.org MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit On Feb 6, 2008 8:38 AM,   wrote: > Hi, > I have a query of how to call Tomahawk in perl. Tomahawk is a tool > used in > Linux for verifying NIPS. I need to get the Tomahawks attribute from > the user and pass it to tomahawk tool. If anyone has any idea about > how to call the Tomahawk tool within perl script..kindly reply. snip You have several options.  Which one you chose depends on what you want to do: system* - you just want to run a command qx//** - you want to run a command and capture the stdout IPC::Open3*** - you want to run a command, feed it data on its stdin and capture its stdout and stderr You use them roughly like this ##system system "command" == 0     or die "command failed"; ##qx// my $all_output = qx{command}; or my @output_split_by_line = qx{command}; ##IPC::Open3 use IPC::Open3; open3 my $in, $my $out, my $err, "command"     or die "could not run command: $!"; while (<$out>) {     #work with lines from $out } * http://perldoc.perl.org/functions/system.html ** http://perldoc.perl.org/perlop.html#qx/STRING/ *** http://perldoc.perl.org/IPC/Open3.html --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98649.ezm" >From kgery.zuifg@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <2be1b0100802061218m716b45e8gf9dc772c116f14cd@mail.gmail.com> Date: Wed, 6 Feb 2008 15:18:53 -0500 From: "minky arora"  To: soiofdvxg@perl.org Subject: SOAP::Lite on Leopard MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/alternative;  	boundary="----=_Part_19842_24026298.1202329133202" ------=_Part_19842_24026298.1202329133202 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Content-Disposition: inline Hi, Can anyone please point me in the right direction to download SOAP::Lite on Leopard? I am unable to find instructions for the same, It will be a great help. Thanks.. ------=_Part_19842_24026298.1202329133202-- --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98651.ezm" >From tgids.sclju@pdf.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <47AAE35B.5070305@pdf.com> Date: Thu, 07 Feb 2008 02:54:19 -0800 From: Mahdi A Sbeih  MIME-Version: 1.0 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org Subject: Deleting a file while other script still appending to Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Hi all, I have a script that logs activities to a txt log file. I noticed that  when deleting the file from another window or shell, the script stops  writing to the file. I was expecting something like the unix shell,  which is creating a new file and appending to it. execute this script: #!/usr/local/bin/perl use FileHandle; open(LOGFILE,">>logFile"); LOGFILE->autoflush; while (1) {     sleep 1;     print LOGFILE ("test\\n"); } After few seconds, and from another terminal, delete the file that was  created by the script, notice that the script won't stop or error out,  but in the same time no new file is created. Thanks, Mahdi

subject: Re: [opensuse] OpenSuSE "Central" management system
body: Peter Adkins wrote: > I'm looking to find a system which will allow me to administer > multiple installs of OpenSuSE at once. As in, I would like to be able > to administer packages, firewall configuration, etc, across all of the > machines. [snip] > Any suggestions would be great, as I haven't yet been able to find a > "package" which does what I require in these regards. I don't know of any such management package specific to openSUSE, but managing the configurations of several machines is usually about making sure all the config files are in sync: cfengine csync For operational management: munin nagios /Per Jessen, ZÃ¼rich --  http://www.spamchek.com/ - your spam is our business. --  >From ebff@sonic.net  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <47A8F37E.4010103@sonic.net> Date: Tue, 05 Feb 2008 15:38:38 -0800 From: boll  MIME-Version: 1.0 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org Subject: Re: removing duplicates Content-Type: text/plain; charsetContent-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Rob Dixon wrote: > boll wrote: >> I'm trying to write a script to remove duplicate e-mail addresses  >> from a list. >> I'd like some help understanding... >> 1. Why does it remove all but one of the duplicate lines? >> 2. How can I fix it? >> >> Thanks for any advice, >> John >> ------------------------------- >> #!/usr/bin/perl >> use warnings; >> use strict; >> >> open ALLNAMES, "emails.txt" or die "File: infile failed to open: $!\\n"; >> my @allnames >> >> my %seen >> my @unique >> >> print "@unique"; >> >> close ALLNAMES or die "cannot close infile"; >> ----------------------------------------- >> here's a small test file with fourteen lines, but only ten unique lines: >> >> pup@ahoo.com >> cnn@ahoo.com >> bgdaz@bcglobal.net >> kejc@bcglobal.net >> wfgc@ahoo.com >> lrq@mail.com >> fgcpm@otmail.com >> kcuwa@ildblue.net >> rdrd@arthlink.net >> vdn@omcast.net >> pup@ahoo.com >> cnn@ahoo.com >> bgdaz@bcglobal.net >> kejc@bcglobal.net >> >> ------------------------------- > > I would guess that your output includes the last line of the file when > you don't expect it to. You are retaining the newline character at the > end of each line. If the final line doesn't have a newline at the end it > will appear different from the ones that do, and so will be listed in > the output. To fix this just > >   my @allnames >   chomp @allnames; > > and then > >   print "$_\\n" foreach @unique; > > at the end. > > HTH, > > Rob > > > OK,  now I get it. The two lines appear identical, but only one has a newline appended. Thanks for the explanation! -John --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename >From xlicq@espiral.org.mx  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Subject: Re: WWW::Mechanize's JS plugin From: David Moreno  To: soiofdvxg@perl.org Content-Type: text/plain; charsetDate: Tue, 05 Feb 2008 12:15:46 -0500 Message-Id: <1202231746.5495.61.camel@petunia> Mime-Version: 1.0 Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable It says you should use the experimental method: > The experimental version of WWW::Mechanize available at  > http://www-mechanize.googlecode.com/svn/branches/plugins/ D. On Fri, 2008-02-01 at 17:04 +0800, J. Peng wrote: > I found this module on cpan: >  > http://search.cpan.org/~sprout/WWW-Mechanize-Plugin-JavaScript-0.002/lib/WWW/Mechanize/Plugin/JavaScript.pm#PREREQUISITES >  > But it says, >  > To load the plugin, just use WWW::Mechanize's use_plugin method (note > that the current stable release of that module doesn't support > this;..) >  > oops since the original module doesn't support this method, how will > the plugin author think to develop that a module? > If I really want WWW::Mechanize to support Javascript, how to do it? >  > (I'm running Perl 5.8.8 and latest version of WWW::Mechanize). >  > Thanks. >  > //Jeff >  --  David.  Juro que ni Sï¿½crates lo pensaba tanto. --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename >From poffm_1276@yahoo.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org From: isaac2004  Subject: parsing html question Date: Tue, 5 Feb 2008 10:36:32 -0800 (PST) Message-ID: <9c948c24-e7ee-47a7-846c-de7b9ea2de21@i29g2000prf.googlegroups.com> Mime-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charsetContent-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit hello, i am trying to parse an html document for links for output, my idea is to grab the URL from a form and send the URL to another file that does the actual parse process. i am aware that HTML:Parser has a built in for this, but i want to learn regex better. my plan after i get the file is to put the new varaible into a loop construct and use a regex cpmparitor to put a match into an array. the only problem is that i dont know how to setup such a loop and grab the whole "piece" of what i need. i have included some code that i have made. i would appreciate any help given. thank you #!/usr/local/bin/perl use CGI ':standard'; use LWP::Simple; ##Declare globals ----------------------------------- $url  $linkstring $imagestring   my $content   die "Couldn't get $url" unless defined $content; #--------------------------------------------------- print header, start_html({-title if($content     $var print "$var\\n";   } else {     print "No\\n";   } if($content     print "Yes\\n";   } else {     print "No\\n";   } print end_html; --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename >From abk@stonehenge.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <31086b240802051540l6cbaa90fub875abd60254a774@mail.gmail.com> Date: Tue, 5 Feb 2008 15:40:30 -0800 From: "Tom Phoenix"  To: isaac2004  Subject: Re: parsing html question Cc: soiofdvxg@perl.org MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charsetContent-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit On Feb 5, 2008 10:36 AM, isaac2004  wrote: > hello, i am trying to parse an html document for links for output, my > idea is to grab the URL from a form and send the URL to another file > that does the actual parse process. i am aware that HTML:Parser has a > built in for this, but i want to learn regex better. Let me know if your technique helps you to learn regular expressions. You will also have the chance to learn how complex a data format HTML is, and why parsers are more complex than simple pattern matches. For other people who want to learn more about regular expressions, I'd recommend the book "Mastering Regular Expressions" by Jeffrey Friedl. REs are a small language of their own, worthy of study. This book has interesting, useful, and practical information for any programmer who works with regular expressions. In fact, when the book first came out, everyone was expecting that any "book" on REs would be a pocket reference. Everyone was stunned at how much of this fat book was news even to the experts. (Several bugs and shortcomings of Perl's RE engine were fixed as a direct result of that first edition.) I'm sure that anyone who frequently uses Perl's patterns, or any other regular expressions, will find this book informative today.     http://regex.info/ Cheers! --Tom Phoenix Stonehenge Perl Training --iliclgfmceejibbpfidi Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename >From cjeibunfyetzcu@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:35 2008 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org From: cjeibunfyetzcu@gmail.com Subject: Help on perl alarm Date: Tue, 5 Feb 2008 07:22:08 -0800 (PST) Message-ID:  Mime-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charsetContent-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit I am using perl alarm within a script and having an issue. 10:27:35 2008 Message-ID: <47A91AE2.9070907@gmx.com> Date: Wed, 06 Feb 2008 02:26:42 +0000 From: Rob Dixon  MIME-Version: 1.0 To: soiofdvxg@perl.org CC: cjeibunfyetzcu@gmail.com Subject: Re: Help on perl alarm Content-Type: text/plain; charsetContent-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit cjeibunfyetzcu@gmail.com wrote: > I am using perl alarm within a script and having an issue.  I want to > access a host by first trying rsh and if that fails use ssh.  I can > get the command to run with only one of the commands but when I add > both it fails.  I must be missing something simple >  >  > Here is the info: > Part of script >                               .... else { $cmd> qq/${rdist} -cR \\$srcdir $ENV{host}:\\$destdir ||${scp} -pr \\$srcdir > $ENV{host}:\\$destdir/'"; } >  > Error I get > Bareword found where operator expected at -e line 1, near "qq//usr" > syntax error at -e line 1, near "qq//usr" > Bareword found where operator expected at -e line 1, near "/bin/scp" >         (Missing operator before p?) > Execution of -e aborted due to compilation errors. >  > I have already set the rdist variable and have even tried to specify > the rdist path. How simply awful. Lets reformat this so it's a little more legible: else {    $cmd      perl -e '        alarm(5);        exec qq/          ${rdist} -cR \\$srcdir $ENV{host}:          \\$destdir || ${scp} -pr \\$srcdir $ENV{host}:          \\$destdir        /      '    " } now from your error messages I would guess that    $rdist  and    $scp  or something like that, so your Perl now becomes: else {    $cmd      perl -e '        alarm(5);        exec qq/          /usr/bin/rdist -cR \\$srcdir $ENV{host}:          \\$destdir || /usr/bin/scp -pr \\$srcdir $ENV{host}:          \\$destdir        /      '    " } Can you see now why you're getting a syntax error? But your concept is far too convoluted. You have a Perl process that's shelling out to another Perl process, that in turn is shelling out to run rsh and/or ssh. Also, where are $srcdir and $destdir coming from? I suggest you rewrite as a Perl program that shells out, if necessary only one level to rsh, and verifies the return status to determine whether to also use ssh in the same way. I hope this helps a little. subject: Re: [spambayes-dev] standalone cdb module
body:
Ralf> I would like to release spambayes/cdb.py as a standalone python
    Ralf> module. Do you have any objections or comments?

No objections from me.  You might check with Anthony Baxter.  According to
svn annotate he is the author.

Skip

subject: [ spambayes-Bugs-1600821 ] Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong	transfer encoding
body:
Bugs item #1600821, was opened at 2006-11-22 00:59
Message generated for change (Comment added) made by jcea
You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

Please note that this message will contain a full copy of the comment thread,
including the initial issue submission, for this request,
not just the latest update.
Category: imapfilter
Group: 1.0.1
Status: Open
Resolution: None
Priority: 5
Private: No
Submitted By: Ivan Vilata i Balaguer (ivilata)
Assigned to: Tony Meyer (anadelonbrin)
Summary: Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong transfer encoding

Initial Comment:
Running ``sb_imapfilter.py`` 1.0.1 seems to raise the following ``UnicodeDecodeError`` when it comes across a mail with 7-bit content transfer encoding with 8-bit characters in it while classifying::

    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 924, in ?
      run()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 914, in run
      imap_filter.Filter()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 785, in Filter
      self.unsure_folder)
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 703, in Filter
      evidence=True)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 190, in chi2_spamprob
      clues = self._getclues(wordstream)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 496, in _getclues
      clues.sort()
  UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)

I'm attaching the mail which caused this.  I know it is not properly-formatted, but it is a legitimate mail produced by a popular MUA (Thunderbird 1.5).  Spam surely is worsely formatted

Someone talked about the same problem in the list: http://www.mail-archive.com/ttrbkgvhb@python.org/msg04543.html

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Comment By: Jesï¿½s Cea Aviï¿½n (jcea)
Date: 2007-09-05 16:59

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=97460
Originator: NO

I'm seeing a lot (>1 per hour in my system) of current spam crashing
spambayes because they are marked as "ascii" but body is 8-bit actually.

Since my milter spam filter crashes and sendmail disables the milter
filtering for 50 seconds because the failure (my configuration, and I
wouldn't like to touch it), a lot of spam is getting thru. About 30-100
spams, everytime this bug hits.

Please, increase the priority of this bug a bit... It is hitting. Hard.


----------------------------------------------------------------------

You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

subject: [ spambayes-Bugs-1600821 ] Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong	transfer encoding
body:
Bugs item #1600821, was opened at 2006-11-21 17:59
Message generated for change (Comment added) made by montanaro
You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

Please note that this message will contain a full copy of the comment thread,
including the initial issue submission, for this request,
not just the latest update.
Category: imapfilter
Group: 1.0.1
Status: Open
Resolution: None
Priority: 5
Private: No
Submitted By: Ivan Vilata i Balaguer (ivilata)
Assigned to: Tony Meyer (anadelonbrin)
Summary: Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong transfer encoding

Initial Comment:
Running ``sb_imapfilter.py`` 1.0.1 seems to raise the following ``UnicodeDecodeError`` when it comes across a mail with 7-bit content transfer encoding with 8-bit characters in it while classifying::

    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 924, in ?
      run()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 914, in run
      imap_filter.Filter()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 785, in Filter
      self.unsure_folder)
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 703, in Filter
      evidence=True)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 190, in chi2_spamprob
      clues = self._getclues(wordstream)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 496, in _getclues
      clues.sort()
  UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)

I'm attaching the mail which caused this.  I know it is not properly-formatted, but it is a legitimate mail produced by a popular MUA (Thunderbird 1.5).  Spam surely is worsely formatted

Someone talked about the same problem in the list: http://www.mail-archive.com/ttrbkgvhb@python.org/msg04543.html

----------------------------------------------------------------------

>Comment By: Skip Montanaro (montanaro)
Date: 2007-09-05 12:23

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=44345
Originator: NO

Do you have a traceback?  What version of SpamBayes are you using?


----------------------------------------------------------------------

Comment By: Jesï¿½s Cea Aviï¿½n (jcea)
Date: 2007-09-05 09:59

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=97460
Originator: NO

I'm seeing a lot (>1 per hour in my system) of current spam crashing
spambayes because they are marked as "ascii" but body is 8-bit actually.

Since my milter spam filter crashes and sendmail disables the milter
filtering for 50 seconds because the failure (my configuration, and I
wouldn't like to touch it), a lot of spam is getting thru. About 30-100
spams, everytime this bug hits.

Please, increase the priority of this bug a bit... It is hitting. Hard.

subject: Re: courier cluster and amavis checks mail twice
body: On 2/11/08, rupert  wrote: > Hello, >  we have our courier proxysetup running, when now postfix delivers an >  email from one host to another it sends the >  email on each host to amavis and back, How can I get amavis to check >  the emai, only once? >  I think I just have to say amavis when the mail comes from host "A" it >  doesnt have to scan this mail. But the problem is i have to enter the >  Host into a config file, and some dynamic gos lost. Are there any >  other solutions for this? > > >  Feb 11 13:36:22 backend-B1 amavis[5300]: (05300-16) Passed CLEAN, >  [11.11.11.1] [87.234.49.141]  -> >  , Message-ID: <91w50s53.5818179@test.local>, >  mail_id: zANUWAM9cFbW, Hits: 2.523, size: 587, queued_as: A8F89D706EA, >  5473 ms > >  Feb 11 13:33:08 backend-A1 amavis[24510]: (24510-10) Passed CLEAN, >  MYNETS LOCAL [172.20.2.101] [11.1.11.1]  -> >  , Message-ID: <91w50s53.5818179@test.local>, >  mail_id: VssPD27B5Ev0, Hits: 2.298, size: 1471, queued_as: >  9EEFF1B30096, 5997 ms > > I solved this the following way: added this line to main.cf smtpd_client_restrictions=check_client_access hash:/etc/postfix/amavis_bypass and entered this line to amacis_bypass: 172.20.1.101 FILTER smtp:[127.0.0.1]:10025 which is the remote host the mail is comming from. Is this the usual way or are there "faster" methods? thx again Heiko >  thx > > >  .r >

subject: [ spambayes-Bugs-1600821 ] Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong	transfer encoding
body:
Bugs item #1600821, was opened at 2006-11-22 00:59
Message generated for change (Comment added) made by jcea
You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

Please note that this message will contain a full copy of the comment thread,
including the initial issue submission, for this request,
not just the latest update.
Category: imapfilter
Group: 1.0.1
Status: Open
Resolution: None
Priority: 5
Private: No
Submitted By: Ivan Vilata i Balaguer (ivilata)
Assigned to: Tony Meyer (anadelonbrin)
Summary: Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong transfer encoding

Initial Comment:
Running ``sb_imapfilter.py`` 1.0.1 seems to raise the following ``UnicodeDecodeError`` when it comes across a mail with 7-bit content transfer encoding with 8-bit characters in it while classifying::

    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 924, in ?
      run()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 914, in run
      imap_filter.Filter()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 785, in Filter
      self.unsure_folder)
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 703, in Filter
      evidence=True)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 190, in chi2_spamprob
      clues = self._getclues(wordstream)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 496, in _getclues
      clues.sort()
  UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)

I'm attaching the mail which caused this.  I know it is not properly-formatted, but it is a legitimate mail produced by a popular MUA (Thunderbird 1.5).  Spam surely is worsely formatted

Someone talked about the same problem in the list: http://www.mail-archive.com/ttrbkgvhb@python.org/msg04543.html

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Comment By: Jesï¿½s Cea Aviï¿½n (jcea)
Date: 2007-09-17 17:37

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=97460
Originator: NO

My version is 1.0.4.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Comment By: Skip Montanaro (montanaro)
Date: 2007-09-07 04:11

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=44345
Originator: NO

I ran the submitted email through the current sb_filter.py in Subversion
(probably the same classifier as in 1.1a4).  It worked for me.  While I
don't use the IMAP filter, any of the SpamBayes applications should use the
same classifier code.  I'm not sure this is a problem in the current code. 
What version of SpamBayes are you using?

Comment By: Skip Montanaro (montanaro)
Date: 2007-09-05 19:23

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=44345
Originator: NO

Do you have a traceback?  What version of SpamBayes are you using?


----------------------------------------------------------------------

Comment By: Jesï¿½s Cea Aviï¿½n (jcea)
Date: 2007-09-05 16:59

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=97460
Originator: NO

I'm seeing a lot (>1 per hour in my system) of current spam crashing
spambayes because they are marked as "ascii" but body is 8-bit actually.

Since my milter spam filter crashes and sendmail disables the milter
filtering for 50 seconds because the failure (my configuration, and I
wouldn't like to touch it), a lot of spam is getting thru. About 30-100
spams, everytime this bug hits.

Please, increase the priority of this bug a bit... It is hitting. Hard.

body: rupert wrote: > On 2/11/08, mouss  wrote: >    >> rupert wrote: >>  > ok, we got it running, we had to add an exception in the >>  > mysql-virtual_mailhosts.cf query, so it only returns accounts that >>  > are not on the local host. >>  > >>  > Is there a way to add the local hostname dynamically to that query? >>  > >>  > SELECT mailhost FROM users WHERE email='%s' AND >>  > mailhost!='backend-B1.fra1.mailcluster' >>  > >> >> >> what do you mean by _add_ the local hostname? if you mean returning the >>  local hostname, then the simplest way is to add it to >>  virtual_mailbox_domains instead of playing with the table. >> >>      > i would like the query to look like this: > >  SELECT mailhost FROM users WHERE email='%s' AND mailhost!='$HOSTNAME' > > Is there a variable in the postfix mysql stuff for this? >    you mean something like:         AND mailhost <> SUBSTRING_INDEX(USER(), '@', -1) ? but generating your .cf on the machine with the hostname already  converted is probably better... > Couldnt find anything in the docs like this > http://www.postfix.org/mysql_table.5.html > > cheers >

subject: Re: Mail attachements truncated
body: >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type N len 76 data KiYsKiYvLC >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type N len 76 data KiYsLCYsLC >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type N len 76 data LyYxMSY1LC >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type N len 76 data MSoxMSYxMS >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type N len 16 data saSttKmuta >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type X len 0 data  >> postfix/smtpd[15907]: rec_put: type E len 0 data  >  > On closer investigation, This is the delivery of a truncated > attachment. >  >  1) Postfix receives a line of text with "." and nothing else. >     This follows from the presence of a type 'X' output record that >     marks the end of the message content. The SMTP server does not >     write an 'X' records when a connection is dropped in the middle >     of delivery. I've set up tcpdump to check it and I can not find just "." line. subject: [ spambayes-Bugs-1600821 ] Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong	transfer encoding
body:
Bugs item #1600821, was opened at 2006-11-22 00:59
Message generated for change (Comment added) made by jcea
You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

Please note that this message will contain a full copy of the comment thread,
including the initial issue submission, for this request,
not just the latest update.
Category: imapfilter
Group: 1.0.1
Status: Open
Resolution: None
Priority: 5
Private: No
Submitted By: Ivan Vilata i Balaguer (ivilata)
Assigned to: Tony Meyer (anadelonbrin)
Summary: Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong transfer encoding

Initial Comment:
Running ``sb_imapfilter.py`` 1.0.1 seems to raise the following ``UnicodeDecodeError`` when it comes across a mail with 7-bit content transfer encoding with 8-bit characters in it while classifying::

    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 924, in ?
      run()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 914, in run
      imap_filter.Filter()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 785, in Filter
      self.unsure_folder)
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 703, in Filter
      evidence=True)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 190, in chi2_spamprob
      clues = self._getclues(wordstream)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 496, in _getclues
      clues.sort()
  UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)

I'm attaching the mail which caused this.  I know it is not properly-formatted, but it is a legitimate mail produced by a popular MUA (Thunderbird 1.5).  Spam surely is worsely formatted

Someone talked about the same problem in the list: http://www.mail-archive.com/ttrbkgvhb@python.org/msg04543.html

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Comment By: Jesï¿½s Cea Aviï¿½n (jcea)
Date: 2007-09-26 04:02

Message:
Logged In: YES 
user_id=97460
Originator: NO

My version is 1.0.4 and the traceback is:

"""
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.5/site-packages/Milter/__init__.py", line
203, in 
    milter.set_eom_callback(lambda ctx: ctx.getpriv().eom())
  File "antispam.py", line 513, in eom
    prob=hammiedb.score(msg)

subject: [ spambayes-Bugs-1600821 ] Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong	transfer encoding
body:
Bugs item #1600821, was opened at 2006-11-21 17:59
Message generated for change (Comment added) made by montanaro
You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

Please note that this message will contain a full copy of the comment thread,
including the initial issue submission, for this request,
not just the latest update.
Category: imapfilter
Group: 1.0.1
Status: Open
Resolution: None
Priority: 5
Private: No
Submitted By: Ivan Vilata i Balaguer (ivilata)
Assigned to: Tony Meyer (anadelonbrin)
Summary: Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong transfer encoding

Initial Comment:
Running ``sb_imapfilter.py`` 1.0.1 seems to raise the following ``UnicodeDecodeError`` when it comes across a mail with 7-bit content transfer encoding with 8-bit characters in it while classifying::

    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 924, in ?
      run()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 914, in run
      imap_filter.Filter()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 785, in Filter
      self.unsure_folder)
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 703, in Filter
      evidence=True)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 190, in chi2_spamprob
      clues = self._getclues(wordstream)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 496, in _getclues
      clues.sort()
  UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)

I'm attaching the mail which caused this.  I know it is not properly-formatted, but it is a legitimate mail produced by a popular MUA (Thunderbird 1.5).  Spam surely is worsely formatted

Someone talked about the same problem in the list: http://www.mail-archive.com/ttrbkgvhb@python.org/msg04543.html

subject: Re: Question re: smtpd_tls_security_level
body: Charles Marcus wrote, at 02/11/2008 10:53 AM: > The man page for this setting states: >  > "Note 2: The parameter setting "smtpd_tls_security_level = encrypt"  > implies "smtpd_tls_auth_only = yes"." >  > I just want to confirm that if I set this to encrypt, then I do NOT need  > to set "smtpd_tls_auth_only = yes"...? >  > Currently I have both, but if I don't need the auth_only, no sense in  > setting it. Since the default is smtpd_tls_auth_only = no, you should explicitly set  it to "yes" to prevent any changes to smtpd_tls_security_level from  exposing user passwords. >From dlnirllc@waikato.ac.nz  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 6 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 13:12:24 +1300 From: Peter Reutemann  Subject: Re: [Wekalist] Adding a new Filter---Jar generation To: "Weka machine learning workbench list." 	 Message-ID: <47AE4168.9030401@waikato.ac.nz> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=3DISO-8859-1; format=3Dflowed > Hello   Finally I solve the problem of the compilation of Weka, and I > also introduce the new filter (filter.java), in the Filters folders, > Now I want to create the .jar document of the complete Weka with my > new filter, I generate the jar file and when I try to execute it have > this error: > = > Failed to lad Main Class manifiest atribute > = > Somebody knows how I have to generate this .jar file properly? Use the ant build file (build.xml) that comes with Weka, using the "exejar" target. More on ant: http://weka.sourceforge.net/wiki/index.php/ANT HTH Cheers, Peter -- = Peter Reutemann, Dept. of Computer Science, University of Waikato, NZ http://www.cs.waikato.ac.nz/~fracpete/           Ph. +64 (7) 858-5174 ------------------------------ >From dlnirllc@waikato.ac.nz  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 7 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 13:17:46 +1300 From: Peter Reutemann  Subject: Re: [Wekalist] How to add a textfile into weka3-5-7Explorer? To: "Weka machine learning workbench list." 	 Message-ID: <47AE42AA.4030909@waikato.ac.nz> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=3DISO-8859-1; format=3Dflowed > Newbie, here. i hava textfile with datasets. how to add into weka Explorer > to classifyuntil i visualize it? > I have check the explorer.pdf file, i couldnt locate how to add textfile > data into weka explorer. how do i save the file into *.arff? >  Its all totally new to me how to print the output files? What format is your text file? Weka can import CSV files (=3D comma-separated values; = http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comma-separated_values) without any problems. Cheers, Peter -- = Peter Reutemann, Dept. of Computer Science, University of Waikato, NZ http://www.cs.waikato.ac.nz/~fracpete/           Ph. +64 (7) 858-5174 ------------------------------ >From dlnirllc@waikato.ac.nz  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 8 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 13:43:17 +1300 From: Peter Reutemann  Subject: Re: [Wekalist] Weka 3.5.7.exe installation problems To: "Weka machine learning workbench list." 	 Message-ID: <47AE48A5.6020503@waikato.ac.nz> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=3DISO-8859-1; format=3Dflowed > Weka 3.5.7 does not work with with jre6.  You need jre5.  = No, this is not true. The *minimum* requirement for the developer = version is Java 5 (=3D 1.5). It works fine under Windows XP SP2 with Java 6. Cheers, Peter -- = Peter Reutemann, Dept. of Computer Science, University of Waikato, NZ http://www.cs.waikato.ac.nz/~fracpete/           Ph. +64 (7) 858-5174 ------------------------------ >From dlnirllc@waikato.ac.nz  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 9 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 13:50:51 +1300 From: Peter Reutemann  Subject: Re: [Wekalist] Re:PATH variable To: "Weka machine learning workbench list." 	 Message-ID: <47AE4A6B.9060009@waikato.ac.nz> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=3DISO-8859-1; format=3Dflowed > You need to point to your JRE installation directory not the Weka > installation directory. > = > Example: > = > PATH =3D C:\\Java\\jdk1.5.0_14\\jre\\bin The Java installer normally places launcher executables (java.exe, = javaw.exe, javaws.exe) in the Windows "system32" directory (e.g., = C:\\Windows\\system32 or C:\\WINNT\\system32 - depends on your installation = and flavor of Windows). This means, that you only need to have the full = path to the "system32" directory in your PATH environment, not the "bin" = directory of your JRE/JDK. By default, Windows gets installed with the = system32 directory in the PATH variable. To test your java, just open a command prompt and type:    java -version This will display the Java version that gets executed by default (the = one found first along the paths listed in the PATH variable). Cheers, Peter -- = Peter Reutemann, Dept. of Computer Science, University of Waikato, NZ http://www.cs.waikato.ac.nz/~fracpete/           Ph. +64 (7) 858-5174 ------------------------------ >From dlnirllc@waikato.ac.nz  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 10 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 14:06:14 +1300 From: Peter Reutemann  Subject: Re: [Wekalist] weka 3-5-7, Environment Variable setting 	problem To: "Weka machine learning workbench list." 	 Message-ID: <47AE4E06.5020903@waikato.ac.nz> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=3DISO-8859-1; format=3Dflowed >  I've set the Environment variable as below >    Path=3D C:\\program files\\java\\jre1.5.0_14\\bin >    For the earlier post, I've followed the same but it has the same error, >    main.class not found program exit. >    I have used the weka3-5-7.exe developer's version. Do i have to do any > other >    settings in my IBM Desktop? Not sure whether it's still relevant, since you already posted a new = message regarding the Weka Explorer... Back to the basics... Try running Weka from the commandline: - open a command prompt - change into your Weka installation directory (assuming you installed    Weka in the default location):    cd C:\\Program Files\\Weka-3-5 - launch Weka manually (assuming that the java executable can be found    in a directory in your PATH variable):    java -classpath %CLASSPATH%;weka.jar weka.gui.Main Does that work? Cheers, Peter -- = Peter Reutemann, Dept. of Computer Science, University of Waikato, NZ http://www.cs.waikato.ac.nz/~fracpete/           Ph. +64 (7) 858-5174 ------------------------------ _______________________________________________ Wekalist mailing list iuxxdkqk@list.scms.waikato.ac.nz https://list.scms.waikato.ac.nz/mailman/listinfo/wekalist End of Wekalist Digest, Vol 60, Issue 13 ****************************************

subject: Re: Postfix on 64MB Ram
body: Simon wrote: > Sorry Marcel de Reuer, That was meant to go to the list not  > your personal address :) >  > That seems to be the problem: > numothersock                  106                  128  >                  128                  128                 1962 >  > I have asked the provider to raise the limit. It looks like postfix  > master thread has the most open sockets. It has about 60 while it is  > idle. Is it possible to limit these. I thought I could stop it writing  > multiple log files and just have one. >  > On 9 Feb 2008, at 16:45, Marcel de Reuver wrote: >> I also had some problems with crashing Postfix processes on a VPS server. >> Solved by increasing some obscure settings like: NUMTCPSOCK and  >> NUMOTHERSOCK >  I believe you can reduce the number of sockets the master  process uses by commenting out unneeded entries in master.cf. I don't know if that will be enough to help you... --  Noel Jones >From wsck@inhex.net  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 2 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 00:10:56 +0200 From: Dmitry Nezhevenko  Subject: Re: [TuxOnIce-users] Is it possible to have a permanent 	hibernation	file? To: enpsfhxz-stvnz@lists.tuxonice.net Message-ID: <20080209221056.GB8983@laptop.deb> Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii" On Sun, Feb 10, 2008 at 12:05:59AM +0200, Serkan Yegen wrote: > hi everybody, >  > After hibernating my system, i want to keep this hibernation file and make > it permanent. > Then i want to boot my linux from this  permanent hibernation file  at every > further startups. >  > Is it possible to access such settings and how? Hi. There is support of permanent swap storage in TuxOnIce. Option is called TOI_KEEP_IMAGE. However you should mount all filesystems read-only since "hibernated" OS image can't know anything about FS changes. --  WBR, Dmitry -------------- next part -------------- A non-text attachment was scrubbed... Name: not available Type: application/pgp-signature Size: 189 bytes Desc: Digital signature Url : http://lists.tuxonice.net/pipermail/tuxonice-users/attachments/20080210/17894900/attachment-0001.pgp  ------------------------------ >From nlnpr@nigel.suspend2.net  Sun Feb 24 10:27:40 2008 Message: 3 Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 09:21:04 +1100 From: Nigel Cunningham  Subject: Re: [TuxOnIce-users] Is it possible to have a permanent 	hibernation file? To: TuxOnIce users' list  Message-ID: <47AE2750.1050401@nigel.suspend2.net> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed Hi. Serkan Yegen wrote: > hi everybody, >  > After hibernating my system, i want to keep this hibernation file and  > make it permanent. > Then i want to boot my linux from this  permanent hibernation file  at  > every further startups. >  > Is it possible to access such settings and how? It's only possible to do this if the partitions that you have mounted  when you hibernate are unchanging. If they're modified after you  hibernate, the information about the filesystem in the hibernation image  won't match what's actually on the filesystem anymore, and you'll get  corruption of the filesystem. If you're able to work within these constraints, you want to enable the  'Keep Image mode' when configuring the kernel, and enable it by putting  1 into the /sys/power/tuxonice/keep_image file that will be found in the  resulting kernel. You can then hibernate once. Resuming will not remove  the image and subsequent attempts to hibernate will simply power off.  The image can be removed by doing echo 0 >  /sys/power/tuxonice/image_exists. The keep image functionality isn't  used a lot, so you might find a bug or two. If so, please let me know  and I'll fix anything problematic. Nigel ------------------------------ _______________________________________________ TuxOnIce-users mailing list enpsfhxz-stvnz@lists.tuxonice.net http://lists.tuxonice.net/mailman/listinfo/tuxonice-users End of TuxOnIce-users Digest, Vol 36, Issue 12 **********************************************

subject: Re: [spambayes-dev] [Spambayes] removal
body: On 9/28/07, Kenny Pitt  wrote: > That's true when reading messages in plain-text format.  If you read > an HTML-formatted message, though, the "Info/Unsubscribe" label is > actually a hyperlink itself and the target for the link is > "http://mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/spambayesInfo/Unsubscribe". Hmm, this is a bit odd. I was going to go back and grab a copy of the HTML content from one of these messages showing the hyperlink, but it wasn't there. I read all my list mail in GMail, so I asked it to give me a copy of the "original" message source and the spambayesInfo URL doesn't appear anywhere in the source. The only mailing list footer is a plain-text only MIME section at the bottom of the message, yet when viewing that message inside GMail there is a clickable hyperlink that results in a "mail.python.org Mailing Lists" list page with the message "No such list spambayesinfo" at the top. It's almost as if GMail is inferring a hyperlink there, but I can't figure out why or where it came up with the link because the spambayesInfo name doesn't even appear in any of the mail header fields. If you're interested, here's the complete message source that I got back from GMail. subject: [ spambayes-Bugs-1600821 ] Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong	transfer encoding
body:
Bugs item #1600821, was opened at 2006-11-22 00:59
Message generated for change (Comment added) made by jcea
You can respond by visiting: 
https://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&atid=498103&aid=1600821&group_id=61702

Please note that this message will contain a full copy of the comment thread,
including the initial issue submission, for this request,
not just the latest update.
Category: imapfilter
Group: 1.0.1
Status: Open
Resolution: None
Priority: 5
Private: No
Submitted By: Ivan Vilata i Balaguer (ivilata)
Assigned to: Tony Meyer (anadelonbrin)
Summary: Classifier UnicodeDecodeError on wrong transfer encoding

Initial Comment:
Running ``sb_imapfilter.py`` 1.0.1 seems to raise the following ``UnicodeDecodeError`` when it comes across a mail with 7-bit content transfer encoding with 8-bit characters in it while classifying::

    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 924, in ?
      run()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 914, in run
      imap_filter.Filter()
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 785, in Filter
      self.unsure_folder)
    File "/usr/bin/sb_imapfilter.py", line 703, in Filter
      evidence=True)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 190, in chi2_spamprob
      clues = self._getclues(wordstream)
    File "/usr/lib/python2.4/site-packages/spambayes/classifier.py", line 496, in _getclues
      clues.sort()
  UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)

I'm attaching the mail which caused this.  I know it is not properly-formatted, but it is a legitimate mail produced by a popular MUA (Thunderbird 1.5).  Spam surely is worsely formatted

Someone talked about the same problem in the list: http://www.mail-archive.com/ttrbkgvhb@python.org/msg04543.html

----------------------------------------------------------------------

subject: Re: Dequeing
body: On Mon, Feb 11, 2008 at 02:26:49PM +0100, Franck ABELLI wrote: > hi all, > i've had a little incident this last sunday that caused 90 000 mails to be  > queued in the incoming queue. >  > how can i tune postfix to dequeue these messages faster  ? Move further away from the event-horizon of the black hole that is slowing down your clock! :-) If that is not your problem, perhaps you should provide more detail...     http://www.postfix.org/DEBUG_README.html#mail     http://www.postfix.org/QSHAPE_README.html     http://www.postfix.org/TUNING_README.html The incoming queue is only drained when the active queue is not full. --  	Viktor. Alois > I can't help thinking of my latest message to this list:  > http://www.mail-archive.com/beginners%40perl.org/msg91979.html >  --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98680.ezm" >From uiaregi@gunnar.cc  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 Message-ID: <20080210085026.11401.qmail@lists.develooper.com> To: soiofdvxg@perl.org Date: Sun, 10 Feb 2008 09:50:20 +0100 From: Gunnar Hjalmarsson  MIME-Version: 1.0 Subject: Re: unwanted escaping of & with XML::DOM Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit Alois Heuboeck wrote: > Gunnar Hjalmarsson wrote: >> What if you simply say: >> >>     my $titleText = 'Die Brï¿½cke.'; > > you mean resolving the entities first? >  > It's a possibility, but at the moment I'd like to see the form of the  > input as a given. See Hidden Nodes for details." --  Gunnar Hjalmarsson Email: http://www.gunnar.cc/cgi-bin/contact.pl --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98684.ezm" >From jkuourpzbe92@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 Message-ID: <613600910802110118n271ca6e4y313551c814a87175@mail.gmail.com> Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 14:48:23 +0530 From: "Rajendra kumar chauhan"  To: soiofdvxg@perl.org Subject: regarding to create a web interface MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/alternative;  	boundary="----=_Part_9171_2448287.1202721503768" ------=_Part_9171_2448287.1202721503768 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Content-Disposition: inline I WANT TO CREATE A WEB INTERFACE FOR A SOFTWARE CALLED BLAT USING CGI AND I HAVE DOWNLAODED AND INSTALLED APACHE WEB BROWSER FOR IT BUT I DONT KNOW HOW TO GO AHEAD,PLEASE ASSIST ME ------=_Part_9171_2448287.1202721503768-- --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98690.ezm" >From trlxetswdxhm@gmail.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 Message-ID: <341924350802110710r1fb03664v6a62879bdd228e23@mail.gmail.com> Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 07:10:33 -0800 From: "Kashif Salman"  To: "Rajendra kumar chauhan"  Subject: Re: regarding to create a web interface Cc: soiofdvxg@perl.org MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit FYI Caps lock is considered impolite. On Feb 11, 2008 1:18 AM, Rajendra kumar chauhan  wrote: > I WANT TO CREATE A WEB INTERFACE FOR A SOFTWARE CALLED BLAT USING CGI AND I > HAVE DOWNLAODED AND INSTALLED APACHE WEB BROWSER FOR IT BUT I DONT KNOW HOW > TO GO AHEAD,PLEASE ASSIST ME > --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98685.ezm" >From godql.lmebe@t-systems.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; 	boundary="----_=_NextPart_001_01C86CA7.A66F4B3D" Subject: regarding regular expression Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 17:44:27 +0530 Message-Id:  From:  To:  ------_=_NextPart_001_01C86CA7.A66F4B3D Content-Type: text/plain; 	charset="US-ASCII" Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable Hi All, =20 I have string like this. D.PRS.WEB.02.10.001.1 and my requirement is that I want to remove last dot (.) and all the characters/digit after that dot with the help of regular expression. =20 Please help. =20 Regards Irfan. =20 Project Lead TSINDIA - Production Line Individual Software Solutions - UMO T-Systems India Private Limited, Pune Telephone: +91-20-30245000/25605000 (Extn: 5406)=20 Mobile: +91 9822 854 227 Fax: ++91-020 25674090 Internet: http://www.t-systems.com =20 =20 ------_=_NextPart_001_01C86CA7.A66F4B3D-- --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98686.ezm" >From wwsddj@telus.net  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 Message-ID: <47B04800.5070000@telus.net> Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 05:05:04 -0800 From: "John W. Krahn"  MIME-Version: 1.0 To: Perl Beginners  Subject: Re: regarding regular expression Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit godql.lmebe@t-systems.com wrote: > Hi All, Hello, > I have string like this. D.PRS.WEB.02.10.001.1 and my requirement is > that I want to remove last dot (.) and all the characters/digit after > that dot with the help of regular expression. $ perl -le' $_ = "D.PRS.WEB.02.10.001.1"; print; s/\\.[^.]*\\z//; print; ' D.PRS.WEB.02.10.001.1 D.PRS.WEB.02.10.001 John --  Perl isn't a toolbox, but a small machine shop where you can special-order certain sorts of tools at low cost and in short order.                            -- Larry Wall --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98687.ezm" >From zxelge-z.uoijf@hp.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; 	boundary="----_=_NextPart_001_01C86CA1.E1BC6C5B" Subject: Tokenizing a string Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 17:03:09 +0530 Message-ID:  From: "Allam Reddy, Thomas"  To:  ------_=_NextPart_001_01C86CA1.E1BC6C5B Content-Type: text/plain; 	charset="us-ascii" Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable Hi All, I have a string "jdbc/abc.xml" which I wanted to tokenize using the delimiter "/" May I know the perl code for this? Thanks Thomas Reddy=20 ------_=_NextPart_001_01C86CA1.E1BC6C5B-- --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98688.ezm" >From qpnysl@senfdax.de  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 Message-ID: <596ce2d42116eea191fe13fcef007ba7@senfdax.de> Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 14:29:09 +0100 From: "Martin Barth"  Subject: Re: Tokenizing a string To:  Reply-to:  MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit On 12:33:09 11/02/2008 "Allam Reddy, Thomas"  wrote: > > Hi All, > > I have a string "jdbc/abc.xml" which I wanted to tokenize using the > delimiter "/" > May I know the perl code for this? > > Thanks > Thomas Reddy hi, you could use split in this situation. @tokens = split(/\\//, $string); the frist parameter to split is a regular expression with an escaped slash: \\/. HTH martin --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98689.ezm" >From i.zmthqjmf@bringe.com  Sun Feb 24 10:27:41 2008 MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: text/plain; 	charset="iso-8859-1" Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable Subject: RE: Tokenizing a string Date: Mon, 11 Feb 2008 14:31:08 +0100 Message-ID:  From: =?iso-8859-1?Q?Thomas_B=E4tzler?=  To:  Cc: "Allam Reddy, Thomas"  Allam Reddy, Thomas  asked: > I have a string "jdbc/abc.xml" which I wanted to tokenize=20 > using the delimiter "/" > May I know the perl code for this? my $string =3D 'jdbc/abc.xml'; my @tokens =3D split /\\//, $string; print 'Tokens: ' , join( ',', @tokens ), "\\n"; HTH, Thomas --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh--

subject: Re: mass-check --server bug?
body:
Daryl C. W. O'Shea wrote:
> Justin Mason wrote:
>> Daryl C. W. O'Shea writes:
>>> Justin Mason wrote:
>>>> Daryl C. W. O'Shea writes:
>>>>> Justin Mason wrote:
>>>>>
>>>>>> This looks a lot like an infinite loop.  The output files haven't 
>>>>>> been
>>>>>> written to in several hours.  Has anyone ever seen this?
>>>>> Are one of the clients running in --cs_paths_only mode?
>>>> nope.
>>> It looks like the message numbers the clients are returning don't 
>>> match what the server thinks it issued or, probably more likely, the 
>>> client is actually returning the message results.  It doesn't appear 
>>> to be an issue with missing messages as they would be re-issued to 
>>> the client as soon as it posted the results.  In this case its 
>>> actually waiting for them to timeout before re-issuing them.
>>>
>>> Are there any zero-length messages in the corpus?  Zero-length 
>>> messages WILL cause problems.  I can't remember if this was one of 
>>> the failure modes (I think I've only seen the clients hang on 
>>> zero-length messages).
>>
>> We should be able to avoid that, surely?!
> 
> Of course, just like anything else. :)

For anybody following along who cares... it turned out it was 
zero-length messages causing the problem.  mass-check now handles this.

Daryl

subject: Re: smtp_connection_cache_destinations by network address
body: On Mon, Feb 11, 2008 at 08:47:36AM -0500, Wietse Venema wrote: > Barak Yakir: > > Hi all, > > > > I'm trying to set my postfx 2.3.2-2 to cache destination by network address. > > > > One  of our major ISP's  has a primary mx record which host hundreds of > > domains. > > > > If I'm using smtp_connection_cache_destinations = foo.com it's working, > > but it's forcing me to set the list with new domain every time I'm > > getting an error from his mail server. > > You are perhaps really trying to limit concurrency to this ISP, connection caching alone won't dramatically reduce the concurrency demand. The Postfix queue manager groups/schedules messages by destination *domain*, not MX host. So unless you can construct a table of domains that resolve to the ISP's MX host (such a table good be built over time and used to route all the mail in question to a transport with a suitable process limit), you can't solve (what I suspect is) your real problem. --  	Viktor. Krahn"  MIME-Version: 1.0 To: Perl Beginners  Subject: Re: opendir Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit MK wrote: > i am trying to create a perl routine to traverse directories (like a  > file browser) that will be incorporated into a more specific framework,  > but for some incomprehensible (to me) reason, opendir will not produce  > correct information when called in a sub!!! Why (the exact same script  > works fine -- once, obviously -- without the sub loop)? >  >  > #!/usr/bin/perl > # move thru directories >  > use warnings; When I compile your code I get some warnings: $ perl -c dirmenu.pl Name "main::ND" used only once: possible typo at dirmenu.pl.tdy line 19. Name "main::dirlist" used only once: possible typo at dirmenu.pl.tdy line 30. Name "main::chuck" used only once: possible typo at dirmenu.pl.tdy line 40. dirmenu.pl syntax OK > #use strict; You shouldn't disable the strict pragma. > use File::stat; Based on your code, you don't really need this module. > sub listdir { >     $dir = $_[ 0 ]; >     opendir( D, "$dir" ); perldoc -q quoting Found in /usr/share/perl/5.8/pod/perlfaq4.pod         What's wrong with always quoting "$vars"? You should always verify system calls like opendir() completed successfully.  You should probably also use lexically scoped directory handles:        opendir my $D, $dir or die "Cannot opendir '$dir' $!"; >     @list = readdir( D );        my @list = readdir $D;        closedir $D; >     contentof(); >     selecta(); >     } >  > sub selecta { >     print "\\nwhich directory (#): "; >     $new = <>; User input from STDIN will have a trailing newline so you have to chomp() it:        chomp( $new = <> ); >     closedir( ND ); The directory handle ND has not been opened so why are you closing it? >     listdir( $new ); >     } >  > sub contentof { >     opendir( D, "$dir" ); perldoc -q quoting Found in /usr/share/perl/5.8/pod/perlfaq4.pod         What's wrong with always quoting "$vars"? You should always verify system calls like opendir() completed successfully.  You should probably also use lexically scoped directory handles:        opendir my $D, $dir or die "Cannot opendir '$dir' $!"; >     @list = readdir( D );        my @list = readdir $D ;        closedir $D; >     $num  = 0; >     foreach $file ( @list ) { >         if ( -d $file ) { -d looks for $file in the current directory but the file name is actually in "$dir/$file". >             print "$num: $file\\n"; >             $dirlist[ $num ] = $file; >             $num++;    # increment $num It would be simpler just to use push():                push @dirlist, $file; >             } >         } >     } >  > $dir = $ARGV[ 0 ];     # stat (eg) won't deal w/ @ARGV What makes you think that stat() won't deal with @ARGV? > print "directory $dir --\\n"; > contentof(); > closedir( D ); You should put closedir() in the scope that it is opened instead of at file scope. > $chuck = <>;           # deals with a strange extra stdout->stdin return If you don't need the variable $chuck then you can just use void context: <>;           # deals with a strange extra stdout->stdin return > selecta(); John --  Perl isn't a toolbox, but a small machine shop where you can special-order certain sorts of tools at low cost and in short order.                            -- Larry Wall --ccponifefjnaljpmnbhh Content-Type: message/rfc822 Content-Disposition: inline; filename="beginners_98683.ezm"

subject: [SM-USERS] deleted messages still shown in inbox
body:
I perfectly understand that the development version is not intended for 
a production system. It may have bugs.

I have a Postfix+Cyrus-Imapd system. It works OK. Messages deleted from 
another email client, say Thunderbird, still show up in SquirrelMail. 
You can even read the body of the message. Albeit these messages are 
dimmed in color and have deleted icon.

Just wanted to share.
Mufit

subject: Has Cameron fractured Labour's lead?
body:
Has Cameron fractured Labour's lead?
=====================================

Hold it folksï¿½  Channel 4 News publishes the first opinion poll since the Cameron speech - and it makes very interesting reading too.

Iï¿½m not at liberty to disclose what it says, tune in at seven to find out more. 

But I can tell you that if you stop a politician and you ask them about the polls they give you a completely different view from what the media tell you. And then again the media then enjoys displaying the politiciansï¿½ contrary view.

So, tonight: the poll. Cathy Newman will be exploring what it tells us - is an election more or less likely?

And you can read the poll results for yourself on our website as we go to air. The results will be published on this page: 

http://tinyurl.com/2nj24f

Bookmark it, save it, and read it at 7pm.


Diana fever
===========

And as for Diana, you guessed it, a whole lot more pictures that give us almost no further information, except that she was blonde, he was dark, and they were both in the same hotel at the same time, and didnï¿½t live to tell the tale.

But it still has some sort of irresistible lure, as if weï¿½re looking at forbidden, secret moments of some distant event. Which of course we are.

See our coverage here: http://tinyurl.com/2eqlcm


Internet fraud
===============

Thereï¿½s a very nasty story involving very vulnerable people being taken for a ride by ruthless fraudsters, involving internet, email and cheque deception, worth about ï¿½8.5m. Simon Israel will have the full details.


Postal pain
===========

Thereï¿½s an uncomfortable postal strike: uncomfortable for the government, uncomfortable for the consumer, and uncomfortable for the unions. Nick Martin is in amongst it, with the detail, at seven.

Read more here: http://tinyurl.com/263t2n

Hamilton docked points?
========================

Thereï¿½s also an amazing story tonight about Lewis Hamilton the Formula One driver, who appears to be being investigated by the F1 authorities over allegations that he may have indulged in a spot of illegal braking over the course of the Japanese grand prix, which he went on to win.

Supposed evidence has been posted on YouTube by somebody who shot the incident from the stands. We are investigating, and mï¿½learned friend is at hand.

Read more here: http://tinyurl.com/27z9p4


Korea: peace on the cards?
===========================

Lindsey Hilsum is in the Far East tonight, casting an overview on the summit between North and South Korea. Can it really be peace in our time? It looks like it might be, but one slightly doubts that North Korea can be George Bushï¿½s Nixonian moment in China.


Secret archive of Haile Selassie
=================================

There is a highly interesting offering from Nick Glass tonight on Haile Selassieï¿½s photographer. This is a guy who photographed the Lion of Judah for many years until the Ethiopian Revolution produced the tyrant Mengistu (currently in hiding in Zimbabwe).

The photographer was never able to leave after Selassieï¿½s demise, and therefore simply went on taking pictures of Mengistu. He hid his entire collection in his attic and now at last they are being displayed, and extraordinary they are.

So do join us at seven.

Jon.

=========================

http://www.channel4.com/news/watchlisten/video/

Business
============

At the time of sending the FTSE-100 index was up 29.4 at 6564.6
The US Dollar to Sterling was: 2.04 
The Euro to Sterling was: 1.44

Weather
==========
Sponsored by Worcester, Bosch Group - www.worcester-bosch.co.uk 

Today
Scotland will be cloudy for a time with some mainly light rain but it should become drier and brighter later. Elsewhere it will be a fine and dry day with light winds and some pleasant autumn sunshine in many places. 

Tonight
Some light rain will affect the west of both Northern Ireland and Scotland, and it will become breezy there. Dry elsewhere with clear spells and patchy mist and fog. 

Friday
Cloudy and breezy in the northwest of the UK with mainly light rain. Any mist and fog patches elsewhere will disperse leaving a dry day with sunny spells.

subject: Re: Conditional SMTP Authencation
body: Oguz Yilmaz wrote: > This is exactly what I need. > However, I think there will be decrease in performance. Because > sender_login_mismatch will require at least one more LDAP query for each > e-mail. Can you propose any way for applying sender_login_mismatch only for > $mydestination domains. >    check_sender_access hash:/etc/postfix/login_mismatch_acl == login_msimatch_acl mydomain.example      reject_sender_login_mismatch otherdomain.example   reject_sender_login_mismatch . > Best regards. > > > On Feb 11, 2008 3:05 PM, Patrick Ben Koetter  wrote: > >    >> * Oguz Yilmaz : >>      >>> Hello, >>> >>> We want to require SMTP AUTH for users outside for "all" e-mails. The >>> important point is "all" should include emails sent to the mydomain.com. >>> In our configuration >>> - e-mails which sent by mydomain.com users to domains except for >>> mydomain.com requires SMTP AUTH. >>> - e-mails which has recipient as mydomain.com is accepted because of >>> permit_auth_destinations. >>> >>> What We want is to >>> - e-mails sent by mydomain.com users (inside or outside of the network) >>>        >> to >>      >>> mydomain.com should require SMTP AUTH. >>>        >> Build a map of all SMTP AUTH login names and the addresses they may use: >>  >> >> Then restrict sending messages to remote destinations using >>  and >> < >> http://www.postfix.org/postconf.5.html#reject_unauthenticated_sender_login_mismatch >>      >>> . >>>        >> b@rick >> >> >> >> >> >>      >>> - e-mails sent by any other domains to mydomain.com is accepted as >>>        >> should. >>      >>> Our configuration is listed below: >>> >>> >>> smtpd_sender_restrictions = >>> permit_mynetworks, >>>  permit_sasl_authenticated, >>>  reject_invalid_hostname, >>>  reject_unknown_sender_domain, >>>  reject_non_fqdn_sender, >>>  permit >>> >>> smtpd_recipient_restrictions = >>>  permit_mynetworks, >>>  permit_sasl_authenticated, >>>  reject_unauth_pipelining, >>>  permit_auth_destination, >>>  reject_unknown_recipient_domain, >>>  reject_non_fqdn_recipient, >>>  reject_unauth_destination, >>>  reject_rbl_client zen.spamhaus.org, >>>  reject_rbl_client list.dsbl.org, >>>  reject_rbl_client multihop.dsbl.org, >>>  reject_rbl_client dnsbl.njabl.org, >>> >>> >>> Regards, >>> >>> Oguz Yilmaz >>>        >> -- >> The Book of Postfix >>  >> saslfinger (debugging SMTP AUTH): >>  >> >>      > >
